## Stack Implementation: Array and Linked List

A stack is a Last-In First-Out (LIFO) data structure. The two canonical implementations are array-backed and linked-list-backed, each with different trade-offs in memory allocation and cache behaviour.

**Array-backed stack** allocates a contiguous block of memory. Push and pop are O(1) amortized (O(n) worst case when resizing). Cache-friendly because elements are adjacent in memory.

**Linked-list-backed stack** allocates nodes on the heap. Push and pop are O(1) guaranteed. Each node carries a pointer overhead and accesses are cache-unfriendly, but the stack never needs resizing.

```python
# Array-backed stack
class ArrayStack:
    def __init__(self):
        self._data = []

    def push(self, val):
        self._data.append(val)  # O(1) amortized

    def pop(self):
        if not self._data:
            raise IndexError("pop from empty stack")
        return self._data.pop()  # O(1) amortized

    def peek(self):
        if not self._data:
            raise IndexError("peek from empty stack")
        return self._data[-1]

    def is_empty(self):
        return len(self._data) == 0

    def __len__(self):
        return len(self._data)


# Linked-list-backed stack
class Node:
    def __init__(self, val, nxt=None):
        self.val = val
        self.next = nxt

class LinkedStack:
    def __init__(self):
        self._head = None
        self._size = 0

    def push(self, val):
        self._head = Node(val, self._head)
        self._size += 1

    def pop(self):
        if self._head is None:
            raise IndexError("pop from empty stack")
        val = self._head.val
        self._head = self._head.next
        self._size -= 1
        return val

    def peek(self):
        if self._head is None:
            raise IndexError("peek from empty stack")
        return self._head.val

    def is_empty(self):
        return self._size == 0
```

```java
// Array-backed stack using Java generics
import java.util.EmptyStackException;

public class ArrayStack<T> {
    private Object[] data;
    private int top = -1;

    public ArrayStack(int capacity) {
        data = new Object[capacity];
    }

    public void push(T val) {
        if (top == data.length - 1) throw new RuntimeException("Stack overflow");
        data[++top] = val;
    }

    @SuppressWarnings("unchecked")
    public T pop() {
        if (top == -1) throw new EmptyStackException();
        return (T) data[top--];
    }

    @SuppressWarnings("unchecked")
    public T peek() {
        if (top == -1) throw new EmptyStackException();
        return (T) data[top];
    }

    public boolean isEmpty() { return top == -1; }
    public int size()        { return top + 1; }
}
```

**Complexity Summary**
| Operation | Array Stack | Linked Stack |
|-----------|------------|-------------|
| push      | O(1) amort | O(1)         |
| pop       | O(1) amort | O(1)         |
| peek      | O(1)       | O(1)         |
| Space     | O(n)       | O(n)         |

**Interview Tip:** Interviewers often ask which implementation you prefer and why. Prefer array-backed for most problems (simpler, cache-friendly). Choose linked-list when you need guaranteed O(1) (real-time systems) or when the max size is truly unbounded and resizing cost matters.

